use the banned weapons, again.

18:01.200 --> 18:04.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Chief foreign affairs
correspondent Margaret
Warner reports.

18:04.566 --> 18:09.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: President
Assad was seen today touring
a Russian air base just hours

18:11.533 --> 18:14.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
after last night's White House
statement. It warned that
the Syrian regime would pay

18:16.133 --> 18:18.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a heavy price for launching
another chemical attack.

18:18.633 --> 18:23.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Today, the Pentagon elaborated,
saying the U.S. has seen active
preparations for chemical

18:25.033 --> 18:29.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
weapons use at Shayrat air base
near Homs in Western Syria.

18:31.733 --> 18:33.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Nancy Youssef is senior
national security
correspondent at BuzzFeed.

18:33.800 --> 18:37.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NANCY YOUSSEF, BuzzFeed: The
Pentagon told us that they saw
evidence of planes that were

18:37.500 --> 18:42.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
used to conduct aerial chemical
attacks in the past being moved
around on Shayrat airfield.

18:44.366 --> 18:48.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We also heard reports of chatter
happening on the ground in
preparation for a possible

18:50.033 --> 18:52.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
imminent attack. The number
of people who knew was so
limited, and the message from

18:52.966 --> 18:57.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the White House was so ominous,
that it created a real confusion
that we are just not used

18:57.633 --> 18:59.700 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
to.

18:59.700 --> 19:02.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: A chemical
weapons attack was launched
from that same base in April,

19:02.400 --> 19:07.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
killing dozens of men, women
and children. The Syrians denied
responsibility. But President

19:11.100 --> 19:16.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Trump ordered the U.S.
military to fire 59 Tomahawk
missiles at the base.

19:18.066 --> 19:22.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Mr. Trump's response was a sharp
departure from his predecessor's
caution about intervening

19:24.733 --> 19:28.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in Syria's civil war. In 2012,
President Obama famously warned
that the use of chemical weapons

19:30.500 --> 19:35.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
use would constitute a red line,
triggering U.S. action. But
instead, after a deadly August,

19:37.933 --> 19:41.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
2013, attack on a Damascus
suburb, then-Secretary
of State John Kerry
and Russia worked on a

19:43.933 --> 19:48.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
deal with Assad that
aimed to rid his regime
of chemical weapons.

19:48.833 --> 19:53.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Trump officials say
that strategy clearly
didn't work, and it's
taking a tougher approach

19:53.800 --> 19:56.500 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to Syria and its key backers.

19:56.500 --> 19:59.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
U.N. Ambassador Nikki Haley
spoke at a House hearing today.

19:59.966 --> 20:02.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NIKKI HALEY, U.S. Ambassador to
the United Nations: I believe
that the goal is, at this

20:02.866 --> 20:07.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
point, not just to send Assad
a message, but to send Russia
and Iran a message that, if

20:09.633 --> 20:13.666 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
this happens again, we
are putting you on notice.

20:13.666 --> 20:18.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: A spokesman
for Russian President Vladimir
Putin retorted: "Such threats to

20:20.000 --> 20:22.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Syria's legitimate
leaders are unacceptable."

20:22.466 --> 20:27.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Iran's foreign minister
said: "Another dangerous
U.S. escalation in Syria
on fake pretext will

20:29.533 --> 20:33.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
only serve ISIS," the
Islamic State group.

20:33.100 --> 20:38.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Since the April 3 U.S.
missile barrage, the
U.S. has had several
confrontations with pro-Assad

20:40.066 --> 20:44.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
forces, shooting down a Syrian
air force jet and an armed
Iranian-made drone. In response,

20:46.233 --> 20:51.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Russia has threatened to
target coalition aircraft in
certain parts of Syria. Today,

20:52.666 --> 20:55.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it's unclear what the
broader U.S. strategy is.

20:55.000 --> 20:59.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
NANCY YOUSSEF: Is the
U.S. committed to a
form of deterrence
against the regime for

20:59.333 --> 21:03.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
possible chemical attacks?
And, if so, in what form? Going
forward, will the U.S. put

21:03.866 --> 21:07.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
out a statement every
time it suspects chemical
weapons attacks? Is
that what we are to take

21:07.933 --> 21:09.433 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
away from yesterday's statement?

21:09.433 --> 21:14.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: For the "PBS
NewsHour," I'm Margaret Warner.

